{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/glandular-fever-infectious-mononucleosis/background-information/prevalence/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"364f7cae-6906-5430-bfa6-9ad3296bd449","slug":"prevalence","fullItemName":"Prevalence","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 2d289577-c91e-45e6-8ec4-e0c520c106e5 --><h2>How common is it?</h2><!-- end field 2d289577-c91e-45e6-8ec4-e0c520c106e5 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item f23b8be3-83da-4e07-b70f-56b81fcba56d --><!-- begin field 1f963b10-a318-4ea7-9d75-23d29f3d692c --><ul><li><strong>Glandular fever is most common in people aged 15–24 years, although cases have been reported in people of all ages </strong>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/glandular-fever-infectious-mononucleosis/references/\">Rezk, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/glandular-fever-infectious-mononucleosis/references/\">Womack, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/glandular-fever-infectious-mononucleosis/references/\">Ebell, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/glandular-fever-infectious-mononucleosis/references/\">BMJ, 2018</a>]<strong>.</strong><ul><li>The annual incidence in the general population is approximately 5 cases per 1000 persons; however, in a practice with a large young adult population, the annual incidence can be as high as 48 cases per 1000 persons [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/glandular-fever-infectious-mononucleosis/references/\">Womack, 2015</a>].</li><li>The annual incidence in people younger than 10 years or older than 30 years is less than 1 case per 1000 persons [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/glandular-fever-infectious-mononucleosis/references/\">Womack, 2015</a>].</li><li>Glandular fever is rare during the first year of life because of passive immunity received from maternal antibodies.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Epidemiological studies show that over 95% of adults worldwide have been infected with the Epstein-Barr virus (EBV), which is the most common cause of glandular fever </strong>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/glandular-fever-infectious-mononucleosis/references/\">Balfour, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/glandular-fever-infectious-mononucleosis/references/\">Rezk, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/glandular-fever-infectious-mononucleosis/references/\">Womack, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/glandular-fever-infectious-mononucleosis/references/\">BMJ, 2018</a>]<strong>. </strong><ul><li>Glandular fever is more likely to affect those who acquire primary EBV in their teenage years. In young adults, the rate of developing glandular fever from primary EBV infection is estimated at 50%, with a range between 26–74%. In older adults, EBV infection often does not progress to glandular fever [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/glandular-fever-infectious-mononucleosis/references/\">Womack, 2015</a>].</li><li>Glandular fever is less commonly seen in developing countries because the age at acquisition of primary EBV infection is younger than it is in developed countries [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/glandular-fever-infectious-mononucleosis/references/\">Balfour, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/glandular-fever-infectious-mononucleosis/references/\">BMJ, 2018</a>]:<ul><li>In developing countries, most children acquire EBV by the age of 4 years.</li><li>In developed countries, primary EBV infection tends to occur later in life, and between 25–75% of people with EBV infection develop glandular fever.</li></ul></li></ul></li><li><strong>There is no seasonal variation or gender or sex predisposition in the incidence of glandular fever </strong>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/glandular-fever-infectious-mononucleosis/references/\">Womack, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/glandular-fever-infectious-mononucleosis/references/\">BMJ, 2018</a>]<strong>.</strong></li></ul><!-- end field 1f963b10-a318-4ea7-9d75-23d29f3d692c --><!-- end item f23b8be3-83da-4e07-b70f-56b81fcba56d -->","topic":{"id":"79787412-82dc-54ee-8f4d-82bb69926abd","topicId":"c9504b30-5339-4b0e-ae98-8637960b13dd","topicName":"Glandular fever (infectious mononucleosis)","slug":"glandular-fever-infectious-mononucleosis","lastRevised":"Last revised in March 2020","chapters":[{"id":"fe86b21c-212e-588d-8fa4-c3ba5660eac1","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"5f9a86f5-ef8f-544d-913a-a590a53535c1","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"0a089fd0-524b-5897-8e6a-ddf549b68ab1","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"4bb31918-f826-5ad9-94c9-277390a6c0a6","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"1b1796e9-9f11-5086-8044-c244b38cab9f","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"e8f82c54-74bc-5c96-8ae4-915ef47cdc57","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"e297f8dd-9da6-5f6e-994d-22be9b9c25ce","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"3046ea37-29e3-531b-988d-b845fd950135","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"4e842d69-8714-5155-a670-debee1452013","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"6002b762-9bc1-544a-8bd4-9a17721ee873","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"91fe23ad-4802-56ea-b009